===Definitions===
{{head|zh|hanzi}}

# [[very]]; [[extremely]]; in a high degree
#: {{zh-x|他 很 高興。|He is '''very''' pleased.}}
#: {{zh-x|我 很 喜歡。|I like it '''very much'''.}}
#: {{zh-x|我 喜歡 得{de} 很。|I like it '''very much'''.}}
# {{lb|zh|Mandarin|especially before monosyllabic adjectives}} {{gloss|no meaning, see usage note}}
#: {{syn|zh|yue:好<tr:->}}
#: {{zh-x|我 很 好。|I'm good. (no intensification)}}
# {{lb|zh|obsolete|original senses}}
## to [[disobey]]; to [[defy]]; to be [[querulous]]
##* {{zh-x|ref=Zhuangzi|見 過 不 更，聞 諫 愈 甚，謂 之 很。|To see one's errors and not improve, to hear words of advice and become ever more extreme: this is called '''being querulous'''.}}
## [[struggle]]; [[dispute]]; [[lawsuit]]
##* {{zh-x|ref=Liji|臨 財 毋 苟 得，臨 難 毋 苟 免。很 毋 求 勝，分 毋 求 多。|When faced with wealth, do not obtain it improperly; when faced with hardship, do not escape it improperly. As for '''disputes''', do not seek victory; as for your share, do not seek too much.}}
##* {{zh-x|ref=Mencius|從 耳目 之 欲，以為{wéi} 父母 戮，四 不孝 也；好 勇 鬥很，以 危 父母，五 不孝 也。|To follow sensual desires and cause shame for one's parents is the fourth case of filial impiety; to love recklessness and '''fighting''' and thereby imperil one's parents is the fifth case of filial impiety.}}
## to [[try]] to one's [[utmost]]
# {{lb|zh|obsolete}} {{alt form|zh|狠|t=[[cruel]]; [[savage]]; [[inhumane]]}}

====Usage notes====
* Mandarin speakers have a strong tendency to avoid monosyllabic terms. In order to satisfy this restriction, 很 is added before monosyllabic adjectives without any actual meaning. Similarly, Chinese people with monosyllabic first names will usually be addressed by their full name, even by their parents.
* Such usage of 很 is not uncommon before other adjectives as well, to the point where forming a sentence without 很 may be perceived as very unnatural. Additionally, using an adjective as a predicate without 很 might carry notions of a [[comparative]] statement, e.g. '我好' could be interpreted as 'I am good [unlike some other person that was mentioned]'.

